- Hytek power points are a metric used to evaluate the performance of swimmers in various events;
- The top performer in each event is determined by the fastest swim time;
- The overall dominant swimmer is the one with the highest total Hytek power points across all events.

- Long swims are defined as those with a swim time greater than 60 seconds;
- Freestyle is a type of stroke in swimming;
- The adjusted swim time is a modified version of the actual swim time, often used to standardize performances across different conditions.

- A 'sanction_id' of 3 indicates a specific governing body or organization that approves the meet;
- 'Freestyle' is a type of swimming stroke;
- 'First-place' refers to the swimmer who finished the event in the shortest time;
- 'Electronic' time recording is more precise and commonly used in official competitions.

- "Top performers" refers to swimmers who placed 1st, 2nd, or 3rd in their events;
- "Average adjusted swim times" are calculated to account for any variations in conditions or formats;
- "Champions" in this context are the meets that have the most top performers and the fastest average adjusted times.

- "Top 10 swimmers" refers to the highest-ranked swimmers based on their total Hytek power points;
- "Total power points" are calculated by summing the Hytek power points earned in all events;
- "Location of the meet" and "type of stroke" are details from the specific meets and events where the swimmers competed.

- '100 FR SCY' refers to the 100-yard freestyle event in short course yards;
- '200 IM' refers to the 200-yard individual medley event;
- Hytek power points are a metric used to evaluate the performance of swimmers in various events.

- 'Individual 100-meter freestyle events' refers to swimming events where a single swimmer competes over 100 meters using the freestyle stroke;
- 'Average swim time' is the mean swim time of all swimmers in the results table;
- 'Above-average Hytek power points' means the swimmer's Hytek power points are higher than the average Hytek power points of all swimmers in the results table.

- 'young swimmers' refers to swimmers aged between 13 and 15;
- 'excelled' refers to swimmers who earned more than 900 Hytek power points;
- 'short-distance events' refers to events of 100 or 200 meters;
- 'time record' is represented by the `time_id` in the database.

- 'Hytek power points' are a metric used to evaluate the performance of swimmers based on their race times;
- 'elite swimming clubs' refers to clubs whose swimmers consistently perform above the average;
- 'outshines the overall average' means the average Hytek power points of the club's swimmers are higher than the average Hytek power points of all swimmers in the results table.

- 'Top swimmers' refers to those who have the fastest swim times in their respective events and age groups;
- 'Age groups' are defined as '13-14', '15-16', '17-18', and '19 & Over';
- 'Hytek power points' are a measure of performance in swimming, with higher points indicating better performance.

- "Grand aquatic stage" refers to the swimming competition;
- "Sanctioned by ID 2" means the meet is identified by the sanction ID 2;
- "Three fastest male swimmers" refers to the top 3 swimmers based on their swim times;
- "Individual event" means the event is not a relay but a single-swimmer event.

- 'Stars of the pool' refers to swimmers who have performed exceptionally well;
- 'Outshine the average' means achieving a higher Hytek power points score than the average for the event;
- 'Under the banner of Local Meet Sanction' indicates that the events are sanctioned by 'Local Meet Sanction'.
